WEBVTT

00:07.005 --> 00:10.089
[bright tone]

00:20.714 --> 00:22.214
- I want some!

00:22.297 --> 00:24.381
- It's the Monopoly game,
only at McDonald's!

00:24.464 --> 00:27.964
With over 50 million prizes,
it's supersized excitement...

00:28.047 --> 00:29.839
- Monopoly.
Do not pass "Go."

00:29.923 --> 00:31.547
Go directly to McDonald's.

00:31.631 --> 00:34.214
- If you were around
back in the '90s...

00:34.297 --> 00:36.923
- Now at McDonald's,
Monopoly is more than a game!

00:37.005 --> 00:38.172
You can play it...

00:38.255 --> 00:39.839
- You heard it everywhere.

00:39.923 --> 00:42.589
- The game Monopoly
is back at McDonald's,

00:42.673 --> 00:44.673
bigger and better than ever.

00:44.756 --> 00:47.673
- This year,
there's more prizes than ever.

00:47.756 --> 00:52.089
- McDonald's ran
the Monopoly game for years.

00:52.172 --> 00:53.714
- Hey, collect
the right game pieces...

00:53.798 --> 00:56.214
- And win $2 million.
- [gasps]

00:56.297 --> 00:57.839
- But no one...

00:57.923 --> 01:03.506
knew the truth about
the game being played.

01:03.589 --> 01:04.798
No one.

01:04.881 --> 01:07.881
["Been Caught Stealing"
by Jane's Addiction]

01:07.964 --> 01:09.506
♪ ♪

01:09.589 --> 01:11.547
- People everywhere
are winning big!

01:11.631 --> 01:13.506
- ♪ I've been
caught stealing ♪

01:13.589 --> 01:16.381
♪ Once when I was five ♪

01:16.464 --> 01:18.214
♪ I enjoy stealing ♪

01:18.297 --> 01:20.422
- The McDonald's prizes
could be cars,

01:20.506 --> 01:24.798
boats, $100,000
up to the million dollars.

01:24.881 --> 01:27.089
- ♪ When I want
something, man ♪

01:27.172 --> 01:28.839
♪ I don't wanna pay for it ♪

01:28.923 --> 01:31.756
- But from 1989 to 2001...

01:31.839 --> 01:34.089
- ♪ Hey! ♪
- I won a Dodge Viper!

01:34.172 --> 01:36.464
- There were no
legitimate winners

01:36.547 --> 01:39.172
of the high value game pieces

01:39.255 --> 01:42.255
in the McDonald's
Monopoly game.

01:42.339 --> 01:46.506
I mean, how crazy
bullshit is that?

01:46.589 --> 01:48.756
[laughing]

01:48.839 --> 01:52.923
- ♪ It's mine ♪

01:53.005 --> 01:55.964
[dramatic music]

01:56.047 --> 02:03.130
♪ ♪

02:38.923 --> 02:42.047
[waves crashing]

02:52.089 --> 02:55.089
[eerie music]

02:55.172 --> 03:02.255
♪ ♪

03:03.214 --> 03:06.631
- Jacksonville FBI had
a little bit of a reputation

03:06.714 --> 03:10.839
of being a Sleepy Hollow
retirement office.

03:10.923 --> 03:14.547
There was a slower
attitude there.

03:14.631 --> 03:15.964
Very undersized.

03:16.047 --> 03:17.130
You know, a fraction

03:17.214 --> 03:19.964
of a Miami or an Atlanta
or something like that,

03:20.047 --> 03:22.255
spread, you know--
spread very thin.

03:22.339 --> 03:25.339
[light suspenseful music]

03:25.422 --> 03:29.839
♪ ♪

03:29.923 --> 03:32.923
At the time, in 2001,
I supervised a squad

03:33.005 --> 03:36.547
of approximately 12 agents
charged with investigating

03:36.631 --> 03:38.881
white-collar crime,
bank fraud,

03:38.964 --> 03:41.756
healthcare fraud,
public corruption.

03:41.839 --> 03:43.422
Even before I got there,

03:43.506 --> 03:46.214
I kept hearing about
this legendary guy, Rick Dent,

03:46.297 --> 03:49.756
mid-career senior agent
and his partner Doug Mathews,

03:49.839 --> 03:52.214
a newly assigned agent
to the division.

03:52.297 --> 03:54.547
- I'm Special Agent Mathews.

03:54.631 --> 03:56.714
When you pull Jacksonville
as an office you're going to,

03:56.798 --> 03:59.381
I know what I heard was,
"Good luck with that."

03:59.464 --> 04:02.547
For big cases, man, you are--
you're like duct-taping stuff

04:02.631 --> 04:05.381
together just 'cause
you wanna make it happen.

04:05.464 --> 04:08.047
That's the type
of division you were in.

04:08.798 --> 04:12.589
I was lucky to link up
with Rick Dent early on

04:12.673 --> 04:16.506
and have him as the old guard,
you know, my training agent.

04:17.297 --> 04:20.673
He's a mathematician and has
about as much personality

04:20.756 --> 04:23.214
as this piece of wood
right here.

04:23.297 --> 04:24.964
Very matter of fact.

04:25.047 --> 04:26.964
And so he and I were
kind of opposites there.

04:27.047 --> 04:29.923
You know, I'm always looking
for another fun ride, right?

04:30.005 --> 04:31.589
If you guys get to Rick Dent,

04:31.673 --> 04:33.214
I'm telling you
he's gonna be...

04:33.297 --> 04:34.547
"Yes."

04:34.631 --> 04:36.339
"No."

04:36.422 --> 04:37.798
"Don't recall."

04:37.881 --> 04:44.964
♪ ♪

04:46.756 --> 04:49.714
[light music]

04:49.798 --> 04:52.339
The priority for the FBI

04:52.422 --> 04:55.589
at that particular juncture
was healthcare fraud.

04:55.673 --> 04:57.422
♪ ♪

04:57.506 --> 05:01.464
We're working a one-
to three-year type case.

05:01.547 --> 05:03.130
That's a long time.

05:03.214 --> 05:05.464
Sometimes I have that ADD thing

05:05.547 --> 05:07.798
of the shinier object
or whatever.

05:07.881 --> 05:11.047
So I see this note
in the corner part of his desk,

05:11.130 --> 05:15.297
and all I saw was
"McDonald's Monopoly Fraud?"

05:15.381 --> 05:16.798
with a question mark.

05:16.881 --> 05:19.422
And I go, "What is that?"

05:21.089 --> 05:22.214
'Cause I'm bored to death

05:22.297 --> 05:24.005
of this healthcare garbage,
right?

05:24.089 --> 05:27.464
It's important,
but I was ready to move on.

05:27.547 --> 05:29.964
I go, "Is this the McDonald's
Monopoly game?"

05:30.047 --> 05:32.005
He was like, "Yeah.

05:32.089 --> 05:33.881
Eventually I was gonna
get around to it."

05:33.964 --> 05:35.881
♪ ♪

05:35.964 --> 05:39.172
So what he told me was
that there was an individual

05:39.255 --> 05:41.756
who had called in
and had this story

05:41.839 --> 05:44.923
that the Monopoly game
was fixed.

05:45.005 --> 05:46.506
♪ ♪

05:46.589 --> 05:48.506
That was pretty much it.

05:48.589 --> 05:50.506
I go,
"Give me that damn thing.

05:50.589 --> 05:52.506
I'm gonna go check this out."

05:52.589 --> 05:53.839
I'm seeing the fun
meter with that.

05:53.923 --> 05:55.631
Like, that's gotta be
more fun than this shit

05:55.714 --> 05:58.297
that I'm looking at.

05:58.381 --> 06:02.297
Dent thought it was
just some BS story...

06:02.381 --> 06:04.255
so, "Pfff, this--yeah, here.

06:04.339 --> 06:06.923
Run with this for a little bit,
young man."

06:08.506 --> 06:12.589
I contacted the source
of this call,

06:12.673 --> 06:13.673
and the source

06:13.756 --> 06:17.005
gave me three names

06:17.089 --> 06:19.839
that were previous
million-dollar winners

06:19.923 --> 06:22.589
and said,
"I know this is fixed because

06:22.673 --> 06:24.506
"these people are related.

06:24.589 --> 06:26.047
"They're on
the family tree somehow.

06:26.130 --> 06:27.964
With all different names."

06:28.047 --> 06:31.214
And the person
who's controlling this

06:31.297 --> 06:35.714
was this nebulous name
of Uncle Jerry.

06:35.798 --> 06:37.798
♪ ♪

06:37.881 --> 06:40.005
So I come back, like,
I'm excited right?

06:40.089 --> 06:41.714
I got the biggest case
ever, right?

06:41.798 --> 06:44.297
And I said, "Look,
all million-dollar winners.

06:44.381 --> 06:45.881
"We need to be on this.

06:45.964 --> 06:47.589
Screw that health--" I think
I probably said that.

06:47.673 --> 06:49.547
"Screw that healthcare shit
we're working, right?"

06:49.631 --> 06:51.047
Or something like that.
[laughs]

06:51.130 --> 06:52.589
I don't--Rick,
I don't know if that was it,

06:52.673 --> 06:54.422
or I know you would
never agree with that.

06:54.506 --> 06:57.047
But like any senior agent
goes--

06:57.130 --> 06:59.005
and this happens
even in today's Bureau.

06:59.089 --> 07:00.631
The new young guy goes out

07:00.714 --> 07:02.714
and finds a nice piece
of gold.

07:02.798 --> 07:04.714
The old agent goes,

07:04.798 --> 07:06.714
"Give me that back,
and let me look at this."

07:06.798 --> 07:08.839
[laughing]
That's about how it was.

07:11.631 --> 07:13.756
- Truth be told,
I was a little skeptical.

07:13.839 --> 07:16.714
You know, fast food,
promotional game fraud

07:16.798 --> 07:19.547
was not making any list
of priorities anywhere.

07:19.631 --> 07:21.422
I don't think anybody
had really even seen anything

07:21.506 --> 07:23.422
like this before, so...

07:23.506 --> 07:27.047
there's always a risk that I
turn these guys loose on this,

07:27.130 --> 07:28.881
and it turns out
it's not true

07:28.964 --> 07:30.881
and that I've expended
resources,

07:30.964 --> 07:33.047
but you know,
I think we all realized...

07:33.130 --> 07:37.714
if this is true, this is,
you know--this is big.

07:37.798 --> 07:40.839
- What Rick did was
immediately get in touch

07:40.923 --> 07:44.631
with the U.S. Attorney's
Office and Mark Devereaux,

07:44.714 --> 07:47.297
'cause if you don't have
an interest from a prosecutor,

07:47.381 --> 07:48.756
you're wasting your time.

07:48.839 --> 07:51.798
[funky music]

07:51.881 --> 07:55.714
♪ ♪

07:55.798 --> 07:58.297
Devereaux was the go-to guy

07:58.381 --> 08:01.839
that prosecuted
all of our white-collar stuff.

08:01.923 --> 08:03.798
- If there's a chance
this thing can be indicted,

08:03.881 --> 08:06.464
prosecuted,
even if it's a difficult case,

08:06.547 --> 08:07.964
he's gonna be the guy to do it

08:08.047 --> 08:10.005
because he's the guy
behind the wheel.

08:10.089 --> 08:13.381
♪ ♪

08:13.464 --> 08:17.631
- That part of the sell,
to get that prosecutor on was--

08:17.714 --> 08:19.673
that was a big deal.

08:19.756 --> 08:23.005
I don't know if Devereaux
knew what Monopoly game was.

08:23.089 --> 08:24.547
I have no idea.

08:24.631 --> 08:26.881
You know, I think
he was a Burger King guy.

08:27.005 --> 08:28.047
I don't know.

08:28.130 --> 08:33.589
♪ ♪

08:37.172 --> 08:40.756
-  My name's Mark Devereaux,
Assistant U.S. Attorney

08:40.839 --> 08:42.631
for almost 30 years.

08:42.714 --> 08:44.589
In this case,
it was, you know,

08:44.673 --> 08:47.005
I don't know if this is real,
or don't know

08:47.089 --> 08:50.047
if it's just somebody
trying to get family members

08:50.130 --> 08:52.381
somehow interviewed
and get 'em in trouble.

08:52.464 --> 08:54.714
[dramatic music]

08:54.798 --> 08:57.464
But lo and behold...

08:57.547 --> 09:02.798
when we received
a list of all the winners,

09:02.881 --> 09:06.005
we were able to show,
through different databases,

09:06.089 --> 09:08.714
that these individuals
were related.

09:08.798 --> 09:10.923
They had family connections

09:11.005 --> 09:13.005
in the local
Jacksonville area.

09:13.089 --> 09:14.506
In my world,

09:14.589 --> 09:17.547
you don't believe
in coincidences very much.

09:17.631 --> 09:21.923
And the chance of having
numerous family members

09:22.005 --> 09:26.005
and relatives win the game
was just astronomical.

09:26.089 --> 09:31.714
♪ ♪

09:31.798 --> 09:35.089
Basically, you've got
less of a chance than you do

09:35.172 --> 09:37.589
of getting struck
by lightning in Florida.

09:37.673 --> 09:41.089
[thunderclap]

09:41.172 --> 09:44.714
At that point in time,
we knew there was a problem.

09:44.798 --> 09:48.881
How big was that problem?
We had no idea.

09:48.964 --> 09:50.172
- The information
that we were compiling

09:50.255 --> 09:52.756
is that their contest
had been infected

09:52.839 --> 09:56.756
years before we became aware.

09:56.839 --> 09:59.422
- I mean, we're talking,
you know, altogether,

09:59.506 --> 10:01.547
potentially hundreds
of millions of dollars

10:01.631 --> 10:03.172
of these prizes.

10:03.255 --> 10:06.464
Well, how much of that
is fraud?

10:06.547 --> 10:07.756
♪ ♪

10:07.839 --> 10:10.923
- Once Devereaux said, "Yeah,
I'm interested in this,"

10:11.005 --> 10:13.381
he's on for everything.

10:13.464 --> 10:16.381
All the strategy sessions.

10:16.464 --> 10:19.339
Some prosecutors,
you see that space, you know.

10:19.422 --> 10:21.756
Devereaux, you got no space.

10:21.839 --> 10:23.881
Right all up in there
with you.

10:23.964 --> 10:25.923
♪ ♪

10:26.005 --> 10:30.589
- So we start with where
could there be the opportunity

10:30.673 --> 10:34.214
to steal the game piece?

10:34.297 --> 10:37.964
- We weren't sure
if there was somebody inside

10:38.047 --> 10:40.631
with McDonald's,
where that person was,

10:40.714 --> 10:45.089
how many,
and how far that went.

10:45.172 --> 10:47.297
- How many suspects
do we have?

10:47.381 --> 10:50.297
We have to figure out
who makes the cups,

10:50.381 --> 10:52.089
who makes the fry box,

10:52.172 --> 10:55.297
who makes these game pieces
that you would pull off--

10:55.381 --> 10:59.464
how many people
are in this chain?

10:59.547 --> 11:00.839
- There's all
kinds of possibilities.

11:00.923 --> 11:03.923
This could be the driver,
the delivery people,

11:04.005 --> 11:06.839
people in the factory,
or even, you know,

11:06.923 --> 11:09.881
somebody in corporate
at McDonald's.

11:09.964 --> 11:13.297
- We didn't close out anyone.

11:13.381 --> 11:16.589
♪ ♪

11:16.673 --> 11:19.839
- So there reached a point
where there was a ton

11:19.923 --> 11:24.089
of questions, but it was,
I mean, very difficult

11:24.172 --> 11:28.839
to pursue that further without
putting some action to it.

11:28.923 --> 11:30.881
There wasn't a lot of, like,
let me just, you know,

11:30.964 --> 11:32.798
at the time get on
the Internet and do some--

11:32.881 --> 11:34.297
there wasn't a lot of that.

11:34.381 --> 11:36.839
♪ ♪

11:36.923 --> 11:40.547
- We clearly had
to start somewhere,

11:40.631 --> 11:44.589
but without
compromising the case.

11:44.673 --> 11:46.005
♪ ♪

11:46.089 --> 11:50.798
So we needed a source
of information on the inside.

11:50.881 --> 11:53.547
- There was a big decision
to be made, and that was:

11:53.631 --> 11:55.547
do we contact McDonald's?

11:55.631 --> 11:59.005
Because we just ran
into a dead end.

11:59.089 --> 12:01.839
- I was sitting back going,
"Don't let 'em know.

12:01.923 --> 12:05.214
I don't want them involved yet.
Way too soon."

12:05.297 --> 12:07.464
But that's me.
And I was--that was just one

12:07.547 --> 12:10.631
little tiny voice, and I mean
tiny when I say that.

12:10.714 --> 12:13.464
- Of course there's
a possibility that somebody

12:13.547 --> 12:18.130
in McDonald's is involved
or knows about this

12:18.214 --> 12:20.381
and is looking
the other way,

12:20.464 --> 12:22.506
but that was a risk
we were willing to,

12:22.589 --> 12:24.714
you know, ultimately
willing to take.

12:24.798 --> 12:27.631
♪ ♪

12:29.297 --> 12:32.214
- We didn't want to alert

12:32.297 --> 12:34.339
too many people at McDonald's,

12:34.422 --> 12:38.839
so we contacted their
head of global security,

12:38.923 --> 12:41.964
Rob Holm, and told him that,

12:42.047 --> 12:45.464
"It would probably be best for
you to come to Jacksonville."

12:45.547 --> 12:47.422
Didn't tell him why.

12:47.506 --> 12:51.172
Just told him,
"You have to come and see us."

12:51.255 --> 12:54.297
That this was
need-to-know only.

12:54.381 --> 12:57.923
Do not tell anybody
you're coming to see the FBI,

12:58.005 --> 13:00.422
to keep it quiet.

13:00.506 --> 13:03.172
McDonald's sent three people

13:03.255 --> 13:06.506
and I personally picked them
up here in Jacksonville,

13:06.589 --> 13:10.964
and we drove over to the FBI
office in the morning.

13:11.047 --> 13:14.839
Mostly it was just,
"Welcome to Jacksonville,"

13:14.923 --> 13:16.339
this and that.

13:16.422 --> 13:19.047
Didn't even explain
to them what we had.

13:19.130 --> 13:21.589
♪ ♪

13:21.673 --> 13:25.172
We got to the FBI office...

13:25.255 --> 13:28.339
♪ ♪

13:28.422 --> 13:31.339
Took 'em up
to the conference room...

13:31.422 --> 13:34.214
♪ ♪

13:34.297 --> 13:36.839
- You know, you're evaluating
their body language

13:36.923 --> 13:38.422
or whether they're twitching.

13:38.506 --> 13:40.047
Are they genuine?
Are they legitimate?

13:40.130 --> 13:42.756
Or is there--you know, is there
something else going on here?

13:42.839 --> 13:45.756
- At that point,
we did not know

13:45.839 --> 13:47.964
if McDonald's was involved.

13:48.047 --> 13:51.506
Every organization
can have a bad apple.

13:51.589 --> 13:53.881
♪ ♪

13:53.964 --> 13:56.339
- This part
of the investigation

13:56.422 --> 13:58.881
was extremely boring to me.

13:58.964 --> 14:00.964
Like, I don't want
anything to do with this.

14:01.047 --> 14:03.005
"Call me when it's over, Rick,"
right?

14:03.089 --> 14:05.923
And--which was sort
of my M.O. a lot of times.

14:06.005 --> 14:07.714
It's way too slow for me,

14:07.798 --> 14:09.714
but I was--"No, you gotta
be here for that."

14:09.798 --> 14:12.547
And I so I think I showed up.
I might've had a gold suit on.

14:12.631 --> 14:15.589
[brassy music]

14:15.673 --> 14:17.339
♪ ♪

14:17.422 --> 14:19.214
I had it in the closet,

14:19.297 --> 14:20.714
and I thought,
"This is a great opportunity,

14:20.798 --> 14:22.964
when it's like a golden
fry suit," right?

14:23.047 --> 14:25.381
Man, when I wore that
in there, Mark Devereaux,

14:25.464 --> 14:28.130
if he could've ripped it off
with his hands, he would have.

14:28.214 --> 14:29.839
He goes, "Are you kidding me?"

14:29.923 --> 14:31.339
But I had a white
shirt on, right?

14:31.422 --> 14:32.798
So I thought I was safe.

14:32.881 --> 14:34.631
[laughs]
I wasn't.

14:35.631 --> 14:40.506
- Doug has quite a wardrobe,
and there he is sitting there.

14:40.589 --> 14:41.714
And lo and behold,
he looks like

14:41.798 --> 14:44.339
he's a manager of a McDonald's.

14:44.422 --> 14:46.714
♪ ♪

14:46.798 --> 14:48.881
- They thought it was cool.

14:48.964 --> 14:50.881
[laughing]

14:50.964 --> 14:52.381
I'm kidding.

14:52.464 --> 14:55.798
So when you're there
in that meeting, very tense.

14:55.881 --> 15:00.547
- I went up to a whiteboard
and started putting names down.

15:00.631 --> 15:04.005
[dramatic music]

15:04.089 --> 15:08.255
And I asked,
"Do you recognize the names?"

15:09.464 --> 15:11.673
- "No, sir."

15:11.756 --> 15:13.464
"All these people

15:13.547 --> 15:16.631
are winners on your
promotional games."

15:16.714 --> 15:18.673
♪ ♪

15:18.756 --> 15:21.381
And then I started
drawing lines

15:21.464 --> 15:24.798
of family connections
and relationships.

15:24.881 --> 15:26.255
♪ ♪

15:26.339 --> 15:28.339
- Devereaux's putting it
right on the whiteboard there.

15:28.422 --> 15:30.214
"Well, did you know this?
Do you know this?"

15:30.297 --> 15:31.756
Brothers, sisters, cousins,

15:31.839 --> 15:34.089
a mother-daughter,
that type thing.

15:34.172 --> 15:38.673
- This person is married
to this person's daughter.

15:38.756 --> 15:41.506
And the names, the last names,
were all different.

15:42.589 --> 15:47.381
And I remember it was
literally jaws on the table.

15:47.464 --> 15:50.047
They just could not believe it.

15:50.130 --> 15:53.005
- Even though we had,
it looked like,

15:53.089 --> 15:55.255
our corporate victim
here of McDonald's,

15:55.339 --> 15:56.631
are they truly a victim?

15:56.714 --> 15:58.464
I mean, there's always that.

15:58.547 --> 16:03.047
♪ ♪

16:03.130 --> 16:04.756
And so, there was
more information there

16:04.839 --> 16:06.297
than I would've
probably put out there.

16:06.381 --> 16:07.964
Certainly enough
for them to see,

16:08.047 --> 16:09.631
"Wow, yeah, we have an issue."

16:09.714 --> 16:12.964
- Everybody agreed that
we needed to keep this circle

16:13.047 --> 16:16.089
of individuals
that had this knowledge

16:16.172 --> 16:19.839
to the absolute minimum.

16:19.923 --> 16:22.464
- You know, Devereaux
was doing most the talking

16:22.547 --> 16:25.255
as he usually does,
and it just seemed like

16:25.339 --> 16:28.130
this meeting just took forever.

16:28.214 --> 16:29.464
I don't even know
if I was hungry;

16:29.547 --> 16:32.422
I might've been hungry
twice in that meeting.

16:35.172 --> 16:37.130
- Proving this case
historically,

16:37.214 --> 16:40.047
which is what we traditionally
did in white-collar cases

16:40.130 --> 16:41.297
when you rely on paperwork,

16:41.381 --> 16:42.923
you rely on
witness interviews,

16:43.005 --> 16:46.506
you rely on bank statements,
was gonna be very difficult.

16:46.589 --> 16:49.297
I mean, almost monumental.

16:49.381 --> 16:53.005
So we would, in this case,
have to think outside the box.

16:53.089 --> 16:56.172
And then we find out
that they were on the cusp

16:56.255 --> 16:57.923
of running another game.

16:58.005 --> 17:02.506
It was kind of a perfect fit
because we were looking

17:02.589 --> 17:04.673
to doing something proactively,

17:04.756 --> 17:06.589
essentially catch people
in the act.

17:07.673 --> 17:10.381
- We told them the only way

17:10.464 --> 17:14.673
to identify this
criminal enterprise was

17:14.756 --> 17:18.756
to have them run a game
knowing that there's fraud

17:18.839 --> 17:20.381
somewhere involved in this.

17:20.464 --> 17:23.172
♪ ♪

17:23.255 --> 17:25.673
- We have this.
We're going forward.

17:25.756 --> 17:27.089
We want your help.

17:27.172 --> 17:30.047
If the answer is no...

17:30.130 --> 17:31.631
nothing happens.

17:31.714 --> 17:37.130
♪ ♪

17:48.339 --> 17:49.964
- My name is Rob Holm,

17:50.047 --> 17:52.631
Director of Global Security
for McDonald's.

17:55.005 --> 17:58.089
Our brand is,
throughout the world,

17:58.172 --> 17:59.631
37,000 restaurants

17:59.714 --> 18:01.881
in 120 countries.

18:01.964 --> 18:04.089
So it's--it's a big
responsibility.

18:04.172 --> 18:07.089
[light music]

18:07.172 --> 18:08.547
♪ ♪

18:08.631 --> 18:11.339
When I first learned
about our Monopoly game

18:11.422 --> 18:14.047
being compromised,
I was shocked.

18:14.130 --> 18:15.714
I was utterly shocked.

18:15.798 --> 18:17.798
How in the world
could this have happened?

18:17.881 --> 18:21.964
More importantly, was anybody
from McDonald's a part of this?

18:22.047 --> 18:24.297
♪ ♪

18:24.381 --> 18:27.172
The FBI wanted
to run the promotion

18:27.255 --> 18:30.297
knowing that it was rigged.

18:30.381 --> 18:32.422
I was hesitant to do that,

18:32.506 --> 18:35.923
obviously concerned that
if this game is rigged,

18:36.005 --> 18:38.381
customers are not
even gonna get a chance

18:38.464 --> 18:40.339
to win the million dollars.

18:40.422 --> 18:43.464
- I think we were naive
to think that they would agree

18:43.547 --> 18:46.130
right then and there
and, you know, we'd be off to,

18:46.214 --> 18:48.381
you know, off--off and running.

18:48.464 --> 18:50.756
These promotions were...

18:50.839 --> 18:54.130
of everything McDonald's,
one of the bright spots.

18:54.214 --> 18:56.381
You know, I remember
the mad cow, and at that time,

18:56.464 --> 18:58.130
McDonald's was, you know,

18:58.214 --> 19:00.005
struggling with
some image things.

19:00.089 --> 19:02.839
- Concern over Britain's
so-called mad cow disease

19:02.923 --> 19:05.881
spread late today
to McDonald's restaurants.

19:05.964 --> 19:07.798
- First mad cow, now this.

19:07.881 --> 19:10.839
- ♪ McDonald's and you ♪

19:10.923 --> 19:14.005
♪ McDonald's and you,
sharing good times ♪

19:14.089 --> 19:16.464
- The most important thing
for McDonald's

19:16.547 --> 19:17.798
is their brand name.

19:17.881 --> 19:20.881
They're a family restaurant
that can be trusted.

19:20.964 --> 19:24.756
Their golden arches
are a part of America.

19:24.839 --> 19:27.798
- ♪ Remember there's
only one McDonald's ♪

19:27.881 --> 19:30.714
♪ And there's only one you ♪

19:30.798 --> 19:33.047
- They have to protect that.

19:33.130 --> 19:35.547
- ♪ McDonald's and you ♪

19:35.631 --> 19:40.839
- And so, if it's on the 6:00
news and the national news

19:40.923 --> 19:43.422
that McDonald's
games are a fraud,

19:43.506 --> 19:46.673
they could suffer
irreparable damage

19:46.756 --> 19:49.339
to their good name.

19:49.422 --> 19:51.047
I wasn't in their meetings,

19:51.130 --> 19:53.047
but I would bet
dollars to doughnuts

19:53.130 --> 19:56.339
that there were a few people
that said, "We can't do this.

19:56.422 --> 20:00.339
Shut it off," and nobody
ever finds out about this.

20:00.422 --> 20:02.255
- They wanted
this big meeting.

20:02.339 --> 20:05.339
And so we went
out there to Illinois,

20:05.422 --> 20:06.339
at their headquarters.

20:06.422 --> 20:08.673
They got, like, this...

20:08.756 --> 20:10.756
great coffee inside to--

20:10.839 --> 20:12.297
you know,
when you walk in their place

20:12.381 --> 20:13.839
and you're waiting on them.

20:13.923 --> 20:17.047
So anyway, I know
that's a--aside.

20:17.130 --> 20:19.881
- And at that time,
we weren't sure

20:19.964 --> 20:22.172
which way they were gonna go.

20:22.255 --> 20:25.005
That was a heck of a decision.

20:26.255 --> 20:29.047
There were so many "what ifs."

20:29.130 --> 20:32.881
What if it's somebody
within our own company?

20:32.964 --> 20:34.297
A traitor?

20:34.381 --> 20:35.964
We've got a problem.

20:37.631 --> 20:39.172
They needed to find that out,

20:39.255 --> 20:41.339
because if they had just
shut down,

20:41.422 --> 20:43.047
it may have continued.

20:43.130 --> 20:44.714
- Look, how many people
been playing this thing?

20:44.798 --> 20:47.714
And they're gonna find out
we didn't help burn this down.

20:47.798 --> 20:51.547
McDonald's knew
they had a ticking bomb.

20:51.631 --> 20:53.756
[elevator dings]

20:57.005 --> 20:59.589
- Making that call
was something that

20:59.673 --> 21:01.172
we took seriously.

21:01.255 --> 21:03.130
Our worry all along was

21:03.214 --> 21:06.297
that this could be
leaked out publically.

21:06.381 --> 21:09.005
So it was not an easy decision,

21:09.089 --> 21:11.673
but ultimately,
we owed it to our customers

21:11.756 --> 21:13.381
to do the right thing,

21:13.464 --> 21:16.172
which is to run the game
one more time.

21:17.839 --> 21:21.673
- We absolutely knew that
if we didn't get this right,

21:21.756 --> 21:23.381
we're not getting another
opportunity.

21:23.464 --> 21:25.089
It's not like, "Don't worry.

21:25.172 --> 21:26.589
We'll run this again
next month."

21:26.673 --> 21:30.089
We knew that, at best,
we had this one shot

21:30.172 --> 21:33.089
to move our investigation.

21:33.172 --> 21:35.339
- ♪ This is how we do it ♪

21:35.422 --> 21:37.547
- From that point,
it was literally,

21:37.631 --> 21:40.047
"McDonald's, tell us
how this program works."

21:40.130 --> 21:42.673
But McDonald's
makes French fries

21:42.756 --> 21:45.798
and hamburgers
and milkshakes and apple pies.

21:45.881 --> 21:48.172
They don't make marketing.

21:48.255 --> 21:49.756
They outsourced it.

21:49.839 --> 21:53.923
They hired a marketing
company, Simon Marketing.

21:54.005 --> 21:55.631
- ♪ This is how we do it ♪

21:55.714 --> 21:57.631
- Simon Marketing actually
produced and came up with

21:57.714 --> 21:59.589
the Happy Meal toys
back in the '80s.

21:59.673 --> 22:01.798
- Your kids will love
McDonald's Happy Meal.

22:01.881 --> 22:03.255
It's food and fun in a box.

22:03.339 --> 22:05.005
- The Happy Meal is gonna
increase your business,

22:05.089 --> 22:06.339
but it's for the children.

22:06.422 --> 22:08.005
- I've got a Happy Meal!

22:08.089 --> 22:10.214
- They wanted
a promotion for the adult.

22:10.297 --> 22:12.089
- ♪ Like McDonald's can ♪

22:12.172 --> 22:13.756
- I'm Richard White,

22:13.839 --> 22:16.881
started at Simon Marketing
in 1981.

22:16.964 --> 22:20.464
- The game Monopoly has
come to life at McDonald's.

22:20.547 --> 22:23.297
- The Monopoly game,
we designed that game

22:23.381 --> 22:25.798
and it was running
once a year.

22:25.881 --> 22:28.130
- A $2 million grand prize!

22:28.214 --> 22:29.464
Play Monopoly.

22:29.547 --> 22:31.506
- It was a ridiculous
amount of increase

22:31.589 --> 22:32.798
in McDonald's business.

22:32.881 --> 22:35.339
Like, 40% when we ran the game.

22:35.422 --> 22:37.047
People love collecting.

22:37.130 --> 22:38.631
- The Monopoly promotion

22:38.714 --> 22:42.673
is much like the "Monopoly"
game you would have at home.

22:42.756 --> 22:45.297
Customers try
to match game pieces,

22:45.381 --> 22:47.464
like Boardwalk and Park Place.

22:47.547 --> 22:49.964
- They had their cards,
and it'd be full,

22:50.047 --> 22:52.214
but they'd be missing a piece
and a piece and a piece...

22:52.297 --> 22:54.005
and a piece and a piece--
'cause those were

22:54.089 --> 22:55.214
the winning pieces.

22:55.297 --> 22:57.547
- And there was low-value
pieces that you could win

22:57.631 --> 22:59.464
food items, beverages,

22:59.547 --> 23:00.756
and then some
of the high-value pieces:

23:00.839 --> 23:03.381
homes, vehicles,
and the million dollars.

23:03.464 --> 23:04.839
- [gasps]
Boardwalk.

23:04.923 --> 23:06.506
all:
Boardwalk?

23:06.589 --> 23:08.506
- So they were after that
million-dollar winner.

23:08.589 --> 23:10.714
You know, people
like chance games.

23:10.798 --> 23:12.589
Any game we did for McDonald's

23:12.673 --> 23:14.214
always increased
their business.

23:14.297 --> 23:16.297
We actually did
Scrabble one year.

23:16.381 --> 23:19.381
Got to where they started
doing it twice a year.

23:19.464 --> 23:21.214
How are we gonna
get our sales back up?

23:21.297 --> 23:23.297
Let's run Monopoly again.

23:23.381 --> 23:25.547
- ♪ This is how we do it ♪

23:25.631 --> 23:27.214
♪ All hands up in the air ♪

23:27.297 --> 23:29.381
- There were very
specific rules

23:29.464 --> 23:32.214
for how you could
obtain the game piece.

23:32.297 --> 23:35.673
One of the ways was
that you could just walk in

23:35.756 --> 23:38.881
and ask, for free,
to get a game piece.

23:38.964 --> 23:40.923
Because otherwise
it was gambling.

23:41.005 --> 23:42.881
How else can you
get the game piece?

23:42.964 --> 23:45.089
You could go in
and buy a food product,

23:45.172 --> 23:47.214
and you could
get the game piece

23:47.297 --> 23:48.964
out of some of the magazines.

23:49.047 --> 23:52.005
Nowhere in the game
rules does it say,

23:52.089 --> 23:55.714
"I can get a game piece
from Uncle Jerry."

23:55.798 --> 23:58.214
- ♪ This is how we do it ♪

23:58.297 --> 24:01.255
[tense music]

24:01.339 --> 24:02.839
♪ ♪

24:02.923 --> 24:04.422
- With a significant case,

24:04.506 --> 24:07.297
an undercover operation
or something that involves

24:07.381 --> 24:09.547
a lot of people,
you could give it a name.

24:09.631 --> 24:11.756
So we had a contest
to come up with a name

24:11.839 --> 24:13.923
among--among the squad.

24:14.005 --> 24:15.422
Some of the names, uh...

24:15.506 --> 24:18.422
Operation Unhappy Meal,
Fallen Arches.

24:18.506 --> 24:21.172
I think there were a few
playing on the Hamburglar,

24:21.255 --> 24:22.964
something about Stale Fries.

24:23.047 --> 24:24.422
I don't think
we sent that one up

24:24.506 --> 24:25.881
to headquarters for approval.

24:26.005 --> 24:29.005
I think calmer,
more rational minds prevailed.

24:29.089 --> 24:30.631
The new promotional
game was called,

24:30.714 --> 24:31.964
"Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire?"

24:32.047 --> 24:33.589
to match up with the TV show.

24:33.673 --> 24:34.923
- Play the "Who Wants
to be a Millionaire"

24:35.005 --> 24:36.422
game at McDonald's.

24:36.506 --> 24:37.881
- If you remember
the TV show, they asked,

24:37.964 --> 24:39.297
"Is that your final answer?"

24:39.381 --> 24:41.047
- Final answer?
- Final answer.

24:41.130 --> 24:44.255
- So that ultimately became
the name of this operation.

24:44.339 --> 24:46.798
♪ ♪

24:46.881 --> 24:48.214
Game time.

24:48.297 --> 24:50.214
Kickoff has started,
and we're in the game.

24:50.297 --> 24:53.255
♪ ♪

24:58.214 --> 25:00.631
- At the time,
I was always looking for

25:00.714 --> 25:03.339
an undercover angle,
even though I was being told,

25:03.422 --> 25:05.255
"You don't want that.
You don't want that."

25:05.339 --> 25:06.714
You know, I was always asking,

25:06.798 --> 25:09.089
"What about this one?
What about this one?"

25:09.172 --> 25:10.673
Go get the bad guy, right?

25:10.756 --> 25:13.089
I wanna burn down
the criminal enterprise.

25:14.589 --> 25:16.673
- Maybe it's the--
the accountant in him

25:16.756 --> 25:18.798
or this Walter Mitty
complex,

25:18.881 --> 25:20.464
but this was the opportunity

25:20.547 --> 25:22.506
to, you know,
be an undercover agent

25:22.589 --> 25:26.005
even before we could
articulate the need

25:26.089 --> 25:28.881
to do any kind of undercover--
that there was always this,

25:28.964 --> 25:30.673
you know, somehow, some way,

25:30.756 --> 25:32.881
we gotta do
an undercover in this thing.

25:32.964 --> 25:34.172
♪ ♪

25:34.255 --> 25:36.673
- Every single meeting,
I'm the one over there going,

25:36.756 --> 25:39.214
"Undercover investigation,
undercover investigation."

25:39.297 --> 25:41.172
I didn't think
anybody was listening.

25:41.255 --> 25:42.631
As a matter of fact,
I think a couple of them

25:42.714 --> 25:44.964
started out with, "Mathews,
I don't wanna hear anything

25:45.047 --> 25:46.547
"about an undercover
investigation.

25:46.631 --> 25:48.297
Just sit over there
and listen."

25:48.381 --> 25:51.422
Rick always coined that
I was the George Costanza

25:51.506 --> 25:53.381
'cause "Seinfeld"
was big back then.

25:53.464 --> 25:56.547
[laughter]
- All right, that's it for me.

25:56.631 --> 25:58.756
Take care, everybody.

25:58.839 --> 26:00.547
- I'd come in and I'd say,
"Undercover,"

26:00.631 --> 26:02.214
and I'm gone, I was out.

26:02.297 --> 26:04.297
- You could kind of let him
run with things a little bit

26:04.381 --> 26:06.464
and then bring him back
to reality.

26:06.547 --> 26:08.297
Okay,
"Yeah, that's great, Doug.

26:08.381 --> 26:10.964
"By the way, I still need
that FD-302 you promised me,

26:11.047 --> 26:14.047
"so why don't you
go get that done,

26:14.130 --> 26:16.381
and then we'll talk
about undercover work."

26:16.464 --> 26:19.297
[phone ringing]

26:20.214 --> 26:22.422
So we get the call
from McDonald's that this guy,

26:22.506 --> 26:26.047
Michael Hoover, a winner,
had claimed the latest prize.

26:26.130 --> 26:30.047
So we had the advantage
of knowing this person's name,

26:30.130 --> 26:33.297
and we're able to do a little
bit of preliminary background.

26:33.381 --> 26:37.005
[dramatic music]

26:37.089 --> 26:40.673
Think he worked as a pit boss
at a casino.

26:42.089 --> 26:43.964
So I guess he would've
been familiar with

26:44.047 --> 26:46.881
gambling and sweepstakes
and whatnot.

26:47.631 --> 26:49.714
- Rick wanted to try
to do the wiretap.

26:49.798 --> 26:52.089
It's a called a Title III
investigation, and it's--

26:52.172 --> 26:54.422
the wiretap
investigation got up.

26:54.506 --> 26:56.339
And, you know,
you're sitting--

26:56.422 --> 26:57.673
you're not really
doing anything,

26:57.756 --> 26:59.923
and that's
a boring situation for me.

27:00.005 --> 27:01.589
I don't know how
many poems I can write

27:01.673 --> 27:03.673
on a piece of paper
to get through it.

27:03.756 --> 27:06.964
So I said, "Look,
what do you think about this?"

27:07.047 --> 27:09.130
When you win,
part of your signing up

27:09.214 --> 27:11.964
as a winner is to say,
"Hey, I'm okay with using

27:12.047 --> 27:14.798
my face in the big check,"
or whatever it is

27:14.881 --> 27:16.506
for future promotions.

27:16.589 --> 27:18.798
So I saw that
as an opportunity.

27:18.881 --> 27:22.255
Let's use that
as a platform for us.

27:22.339 --> 27:24.089
♪ ♪

27:24.172 --> 27:26.422
I said, "I think this
is a great opportunity

27:26.506 --> 27:29.005
"for an undercover
investigation where we do

27:29.089 --> 27:32.297
"this TV commercial
of the winners

27:32.381 --> 27:34.422
"like Publishers
Clearing House.

27:34.506 --> 27:37.089
"Jumping up, telling us
how they won these

27:37.172 --> 27:39.089
"and what they did with it,
that kind of thing.

27:39.172 --> 27:41.923
"So we could do
that with Hoover.

27:42.005 --> 27:44.255
"You know, we're
the production company.

27:44.339 --> 27:45.506
That's how this could roll."

27:45.589 --> 27:47.964
He's like, "Mathews,
who's gonna do this?

27:48.047 --> 27:49.839
You gonna do it?
'Cause I'm not doing it."

27:49.923 --> 27:52.130
And I said,
"Yeah, I'm gonna do it."

27:52.214 --> 27:54.297
He goes, "Well, you don't
know anything about that."

27:54.381 --> 27:57.172
And I said,
"I'm gonna be the director.

27:57.255 --> 27:58.839
"Because they don't do shit.

27:58.923 --> 28:02.339
"And then I'm gonna
get McDonald's to give me

28:02.422 --> 28:04.464
their public relations."

28:04.547 --> 28:05.631
That's all I said.

28:05.714 --> 28:07.422
And Rick goes, "Wait a minute.

28:07.506 --> 28:09.923
"If we're going
to do anything,

28:10.005 --> 28:12.839
we're gonna need
SAC authority."

28:12.923 --> 28:18.255
♪ ♪

28:20.756 --> 28:23.130
- I'm Tom Kneir.
I was the special agent

28:23.214 --> 28:26.631
in charge of the Jacksonville
office of the FBI.

28:26.714 --> 28:30.547
In each office, you have
the SAC for the office.

28:30.631 --> 28:32.547
That's their
Special Agent in Charge.

28:32.631 --> 28:34.464
And then you have squads.

28:34.547 --> 28:40.381
Most of the contact is usually
with the squad supervisor.

28:40.464 --> 28:42.714
But this was--this
was a particular case

28:42.798 --> 28:46.714
that, you know, I had
a lot of hands-on with Chris

28:46.798 --> 28:48.798
and everybody that
worked on that case.

28:49.964 --> 28:52.214
Doug was almost
brand new at the time,

28:52.297 --> 28:55.381
and he's been given
a badge, a gun,

28:55.464 --> 28:56.881
and some credentials,

28:56.964 --> 28:59.381
and now he's got
a Superman's cape, right?

28:59.464 --> 29:01.464
[laughing]
And away he goes.

29:01.547 --> 29:04.255
- So the next day,
I think I was called.

29:04.339 --> 29:06.631
And he said, "Hey,
you need to come up here."

29:06.714 --> 29:08.589
When you hear your name,

29:08.673 --> 29:11.589
"Mathews
to the SAC's office,"

29:11.673 --> 29:12.881
never good.

29:12.964 --> 29:14.631
Never, ever good.

29:14.714 --> 29:16.714
And everybody knows.
It's like the walk of shame.

29:16.798 --> 29:18.673
To the elevators, whatever.

29:18.756 --> 29:20.089
"Oh, shit, Mathews.

29:20.172 --> 29:21.839
I hope you still
have a paycheck."

29:21.923 --> 29:24.047
'Cause they all know it's bad.

29:25.172 --> 29:28.839
And so I come in
and it's SAC Kneir, CDC,

29:28.923 --> 29:32.089
the Chief Division Council,
Rick Dent, Graham,

29:32.172 --> 29:36.005
in this room about
this size, so small.

29:36.089 --> 29:37.923
♪ ♪

29:38.005 --> 29:40.839
And they all, like, turned
to look at me, and I'm like...

29:41.839 --> 29:43.130
And I go, "I'm sorry."

29:43.214 --> 29:44.631
That's all I said.

29:44.714 --> 29:46.047
And Rick goes,

29:46.130 --> 29:49.255
"You know,
I think this might work.

29:49.339 --> 29:51.214
And he's gonna do it."

29:51.297 --> 29:54.714
And that right then was
probably--if I was ever, like,

29:54.798 --> 29:56.547
concerned about,
"I don't know, man.

29:56.631 --> 29:58.005
This might get somewhere--"
you know, whatever,

29:58.089 --> 29:59.589
be careful what
you ask for, thing?

29:59.673 --> 30:01.506
Maybe that was
the moment for me,

30:01.589 --> 30:03.881
but it quickly passed
and I was back in.

30:03.964 --> 30:05.714
♪ ♪

30:05.798 --> 30:07.422
- We didn't have
a lot of undercover agents

30:07.506 --> 30:08.839
in Jacksonville.

30:08.923 --> 30:11.339
You know, you could call
headquarters and say,

30:11.422 --> 30:14.631
"Hey, you know, we need
a undercover agent down here."

30:14.714 --> 30:16.798
"Well, he's not available
for three weeks,"

30:16.881 --> 30:18.339
and, you know.
And so we--we'd just

30:18.422 --> 30:20.047
kind of rolled the dice
and said, "You know what?

30:20.130 --> 30:22.089
Doug is a little bit
of an actor anyway,"

30:22.172 --> 30:24.172
so I guess that's
when my hair turned white.

30:24.255 --> 30:25.839
[laughs]
No.

30:25.923 --> 30:28.506
- Being an undercover agent,
it's not just something

30:28.589 --> 30:30.798
you raise your hand
and decide to do.

30:30.881 --> 30:33.297
You know, there's
a stringent process, a school,

30:33.381 --> 30:36.798
testing, all these things
that didn't exactly mesh

30:36.881 --> 30:39.798
with Doug's concept
of being undercover.

30:39.881 --> 30:41.798
You know, he wanted to...

30:41.881 --> 30:44.255
wanted to get right
up there on stage.

30:44.339 --> 30:47.673
♪ ♪

30:47.756 --> 30:49.673
- He was not
a certified undercover,

30:49.756 --> 30:51.381
but for a specific case,

30:51.464 --> 30:53.673
you can get what
they call SAC authority

30:53.756 --> 30:57.172
to do undercover work,
and that's what Doug Mathews

30:57.255 --> 30:59.381
did just for that
specific case.

30:59.464 --> 31:03.005
My name's Janet Pellicciotti,
and I was a special agent

31:03.089 --> 31:05.172
for the FBI in
the Jacksonville Division.

31:05.255 --> 31:06.756
I was our undercover
coordinator also,

31:06.839 --> 31:10.172
and I tried to get him
to become an undercover agent

31:10.255 --> 31:11.839
because he was just--
he was a natural.

31:11.923 --> 31:14.464
Undercover was like acting,
only...

31:14.547 --> 31:15.673
it's real.

31:15.756 --> 31:18.464
You know, you sit there
and there's a real threat,

31:18.547 --> 31:20.506
and somebody could harm you.

31:20.589 --> 31:21.756
They could really harm you.

31:21.839 --> 31:23.255
- The Jacksonville Division,

31:23.339 --> 31:25.756
if you talk
to Agent Pellicciotti,

31:25.839 --> 31:29.255
is a small division that
didn't do a lot of this.

31:32.089 --> 31:33.714
- Right, so I got
to do all the fun

31:33.798 --> 31:35.881
and not have to go through
all the bullshit.

31:35.964 --> 31:38.798
Yeah, just make it happen.
That's what it was.

31:38.881 --> 31:40.339
"Hey, Mathews,
just make it happen."

31:40.422 --> 31:41.756
And I'm thinking to myself...

31:43.631 --> 31:44.756
And then two is...

31:45.714 --> 31:48.172
[jazzy music]

31:48.255 --> 31:50.047
- He wanted to be thrown
into the lion's den,

31:50.130 --> 31:53.214
and he wouldn't have gotten
it if the SAC did not feel

31:53.297 --> 31:55.047
he could handle himself.

31:55.130 --> 31:57.881
So they got some
undercovers, you know,

31:57.964 --> 31:59.964
to act as a film crew.

32:00.964 --> 32:04.381
- My name is Jan Garvin,
and I was videographer.

32:04.464 --> 32:07.047
When I answered
his call, he said,

32:07.130 --> 32:08.339
"You're gonna love this."

32:08.422 --> 32:09.923
Not, "Hey, Jan,
how's it going?

32:10.005 --> 32:11.214
Let's go, you know--
how was the trip?"

32:11.297 --> 32:13.130
You know, it was like,
"You're gonna love this."

32:13.214 --> 32:15.881
And after he explained
what it was, it was like...

32:18.089 --> 32:19.172
And...

32:21.839 --> 32:24.756
♪ ♪

32:24.839 --> 32:27.714
- We needed to put together
what appears to be

32:27.798 --> 32:29.839
a legitimate
production company.

32:29.923 --> 32:32.464
A video person,
an audio person,

32:32.547 --> 32:35.589
a director and a--
an interviewer.

32:35.673 --> 32:38.005
- I go, "Yeah, I need
one just to act like

32:38.089 --> 32:39.756
"they're the lighting
person or whatever.

32:39.839 --> 32:42.047
"Nobody needs to see
that you're Bureau, right?

32:42.130 --> 32:44.172
"So give me somebody that's
not stupid, 'cause,

32:44.255 --> 32:45.923
you know, we don't
know jack, right?"

32:46.005 --> 32:48.714
In my mind I just thought,
you know, just get on the stage

32:48.798 --> 32:52.005
and everything will be fine;
you'll just roll right through.

32:52.089 --> 32:56.255
♪ ♪

32:56.339 --> 32:57.798
- With any production company

32:57.881 --> 32:59.547
and any good
undercover operation,

32:59.631 --> 33:01.506
you need a good name
and in this case,

33:01.589 --> 33:03.881
we came up with
Shamrock Productions.

33:03.964 --> 33:06.839
♪ ♪

33:06.923 --> 33:09.047
Which is good,
but I always liked the byline,

33:09.130 --> 33:11.172
"'Cause you're just lucky."

33:12.172 --> 33:14.047
- That was--that was good.

33:14.130 --> 33:18.798
♪ ♪

33:18.881 --> 33:21.547
- We thought about
having everybody

33:21.631 --> 33:25.756
in this undercover
operation be FBI personnel.

33:25.839 --> 33:27.547
They legitimately tried
to make that happen.

33:27.631 --> 33:32.464
It just--the way that
this scenario had to run,

33:32.547 --> 33:35.839
you needed somebody
inside McDonald's

33:35.923 --> 33:38.089
with that background.

33:38.172 --> 33:40.798
That would be hard to fake.

33:40.881 --> 33:43.839
[light music]

33:43.923 --> 33:46.214
♪ ♪

33:46.297 --> 33:48.839
- My name's Amy Murray.

33:48.923 --> 33:52.214
I've been with McDonald's
for 22 years.

33:52.297 --> 33:54.005
♪ ♪

33:54.089 --> 33:56.547
The FBI investigation
happened 17 years ago,

33:56.631 --> 33:59.172
and it's been years
since I've talked to anyone,

33:59.255 --> 34:01.964
so, in fact, I don't really
tell the story that much

34:02.047 --> 34:03.547
because, you know,

34:03.631 --> 34:05.547
how do you drop
into conversation that

34:05.631 --> 34:07.798
you're part
of an FBI investigation?

34:07.881 --> 34:10.714
♪ ♪

34:10.798 --> 34:14.964
Back in 2001, I was in
the communications department.

34:15.047 --> 34:17.506
I had only been
working on Monopoly and games

34:17.589 --> 34:19.297
for about six months.

34:20.589 --> 34:24.089
My boss's boss called me into
his office and he was like,

34:24.172 --> 34:26.506
"Amy, the FBI has contacted us.

34:26.589 --> 34:31.172
"They've told us that the game
pieces are being stolen

34:31.255 --> 34:34.881
"and that the entire game
may be compromised

34:34.964 --> 34:36.589
by a criminal ring."

34:36.673 --> 34:40.673
And if you can imagine,
I was completely shocked.

34:42.130 --> 34:45.214
You know, I felt sick
to my stomach.

34:45.297 --> 34:49.005
To break that trust
was just devastating.

34:49.089 --> 34:50.798
How could this possibly happen?

34:50.881 --> 34:53.255
I started thinking back
to all the answers

34:53.339 --> 34:55.756
that I've heard from
Monopoly winners in the past,

34:55.839 --> 34:59.047
and it did seem like
they were almost scripted.

34:59.839 --> 35:02.172
Hindsight's 20/20,
and I started to realize

35:02.255 --> 35:05.089
that it did seem like
there was a pattern.

35:05.172 --> 35:08.172
You know, I used that word,
"pattern" and I think that

35:08.255 --> 35:10.464
was when the FBI really said,

35:10.547 --> 35:13.756
"It would be great
to talk to Amy directly,

35:13.839 --> 35:16.422
since she has so much contact
with the winners."

35:16.506 --> 35:18.422
♪ ♪

35:18.506 --> 35:21.589
- For a civilian to participate
in an undercover operation

35:21.673 --> 35:24.756
doesn't happen much at all,
for obvious reasons, right?

35:24.839 --> 35:27.589
It's--if something happens,

35:27.673 --> 35:29.839
you want people who are
professionals that are

35:29.923 --> 35:32.089
used to being
in situations like that.

35:32.172 --> 35:35.047
- I was a little concerned,
because I wanted to make sure

35:35.130 --> 35:38.798
that her safety and security
was first and foremost.

35:38.881 --> 35:42.506
They said, "Rob, don't worry.
She will be safe."

35:42.589 --> 35:44.631
♪ ♪

35:44.714 --> 35:47.464
- We really didn't know
how far we would have to go

35:47.547 --> 35:49.673
to help the FBI get evidence,

35:49.756 --> 35:52.422
and yes,
there were nerves involved,

35:52.506 --> 35:54.756
and I was nervous.

35:54.839 --> 35:56.172
But I was all-in.

35:56.255 --> 35:59.130
You know, I wanted to make
it right as fast as possible.

35:59.214 --> 36:03.255
So I would be talking
to the FBI sometimes every day,

36:03.339 --> 36:04.631
sometimes twice a day.

36:04.714 --> 36:07.339
People were intrigued, like,
"What's this special project?"

36:07.422 --> 36:09.547
I just couldn't talk
about this, not to my family,

36:09.631 --> 36:12.255
not to my closest friends,

36:12.339 --> 36:14.089
not even to coworkers.

36:15.547 --> 36:17.172
- We told a couple people

36:17.255 --> 36:19.214
in McDonald's and then
our team; that's it.

36:19.297 --> 36:21.589
'Cause we still didn't know,
you gotta remember--

36:21.673 --> 36:24.089
like, this investigation--
we still didn't know

36:24.172 --> 36:26.547
if anybody was infected

36:26.631 --> 36:28.839
through corporate,
right, or who.

36:28.923 --> 36:31.673
- So we set up a time for

36:31.756 --> 36:34.714
Shamrock Productions to go up

36:34.798 --> 36:37.255
and visit Mr. Hoover.

36:38.422 --> 36:41.381
- He had already been
in contact with Amy,

36:41.464 --> 36:44.923
and he was very amenable
to us coming by to film

36:45.005 --> 36:47.714
this commercial that
we were putting together.

36:47.798 --> 36:50.297
- I'll never forget
showing up at an airport,

36:50.381 --> 36:53.673
and a white van pulled up
with all of the FBI agents

36:53.756 --> 36:56.464
and, you know, they're like,
you know, "Hi, Amy."

36:56.547 --> 36:58.172
And I was introduced
to all of them.

36:58.255 --> 36:59.756
You know, I really
had to talk to Doug about,

36:59.839 --> 37:01.506
"This is what
a producer would do;

37:01.589 --> 37:03.214
this is what
the cameraman would do."

37:03.297 --> 37:05.172
And I was just playing myself.

37:06.714 --> 37:08.589
- So the first time
we're going out there,

37:08.673 --> 37:10.214
I think I had,
like, a golf shirt on.

37:10.297 --> 37:12.381
I looked like maybe
I'd played nine holes

37:12.464 --> 37:13.964
or something like that.

37:14.047 --> 37:16.005
That's what Amy told me
what a director looks like--

37:16.089 --> 37:18.589
looks like somebody that's
just come off the golf course.

37:18.673 --> 37:20.964
[laughs]
So I'm excited, right?

37:21.047 --> 37:24.714
But I have a lot
of apprehension as well.

37:24.798 --> 37:25.923
It's the first one.

37:26.005 --> 37:27.839
You want it to be seamless,

37:27.923 --> 37:30.214
and you don't know
what to expect.

37:30.297 --> 37:33.172
- As an agent, you know,
you wanna carry a gun

37:33.255 --> 37:35.214
and wear a bulletproof vest.

37:35.297 --> 37:37.589
But in a situation like this,
an undercover operation,

37:37.673 --> 37:39.255
that may be too much risk.

37:39.339 --> 37:41.839
You can wear an ankle holster
and then, you know,

37:41.923 --> 37:43.130
and then you sit down
in a chair,

37:43.214 --> 37:44.881
and somebody sees it, so...

37:44.964 --> 37:48.631
- You had that little extra
antenna going up to make sure

37:48.714 --> 37:51.673
you don't say anything
or do anything

37:51.756 --> 37:54.172
that would trigger
their suspect to look at you

37:54.255 --> 37:56.714
crossways and go, "Oh, hmm..."

37:57.881 --> 37:59.506
- I had butterflies
in my stomach.

37:59.589 --> 38:02.881
I was nervous about not
wrecking the investigation.

38:02.964 --> 38:05.422
You know, I really wanted
to make sure I did a good job,

38:05.506 --> 38:07.964
that I wasn't
causing any suspicion.

38:08.047 --> 38:11.172
It's an adrenaline that
happens through your system.

38:11.255 --> 38:14.297
You know, you feel
fully awake and alive.

38:14.381 --> 38:15.297
♪ ♪

38:15.381 --> 38:17.547
- She was very nervous,
and I'm like,

38:17.631 --> 38:19.130
"You talk to these people
all the time, right?"

38:19.214 --> 38:20.839
"Well, yeah,
but not like this."

38:20.923 --> 38:22.589
And I go,
"There's not like this.

38:22.673 --> 38:25.297
"You don't know anything
about our investigation.

38:25.381 --> 38:27.297
They don't either,
so forget about that."

38:27.381 --> 38:28.631
She's laughing, like,

38:28.714 --> 38:30.547
"How am I supposed to forget
about that?", right?

38:30.631 --> 38:32.130
And I said, "You got
to forget about that

38:32.214 --> 38:34.673
and just do what
you normally do."

38:35.589 --> 38:37.464
"We're very close to the exit.
We know where it is.

38:37.547 --> 38:39.798
"Just stay as close as you can

38:39.881 --> 38:41.881
'cause I don't know
what to expect."

38:41.964 --> 38:45.130
- Any civilian that you bring
in, you're gonna tell them,

38:45.214 --> 38:48.214
"We have a team.
There's always a team outside.

38:48.297 --> 38:50.756
♪ ♪

38:50.839 --> 38:53.923
"If anything happens,
they'll be there immediately

38:54.005 --> 38:56.464
to make sure
you're safe and secure."

38:56.547 --> 38:59.297
- We have distress calls,
things like that.

38:59.381 --> 39:02.756
So if the undercover agent
says a certain word, you know,

39:02.839 --> 39:05.255
"I feel like
a terrible flu is coming on,"

39:05.339 --> 39:07.297
something's really gone wrong;
we got a problem.

39:07.381 --> 39:08.881
[knocking]

39:08.964 --> 39:12.297
- And so they went
to his home.

39:12.381 --> 39:15.005
They came in...

39:15.089 --> 39:18.506
and so you have the FBI agents,
unbeknownst to Mr. Hoover,

39:18.589 --> 39:20.673
with the cameras
on their shoulder.

39:20.756 --> 39:23.089
- If we were set up to record

39:23.172 --> 39:26.506
pretty much anything, we would
hit the record button.

39:26.589 --> 39:28.464
You never know
what you're gonna capture.

39:28.547 --> 39:31.339
Always gold when
they don't know it.

39:31.422 --> 39:34.214
- The greatest thing
in the world about all this

39:34.297 --> 39:35.506
is what?

39:35.589 --> 39:37.214
We had a camera rolling.

39:37.297 --> 39:41.506
♪ ♪

39:41.589 --> 39:44.172
[indistinct chatter]

39:44.255 --> 39:45.547
- [laughs]
- What was that?

39:45.631 --> 39:46.714
- You think you
could take that

39:46.798 --> 39:48.005
to your local bank to cash?

39:48.089 --> 39:50.381
- I doubt it.
[laughs] I doubt it.

39:50.464 --> 39:51.923
- [indistinct]
We'll do this at the end.

39:52.005 --> 39:54.756
- Amy, she, you know,
worked her McDonald's magic,

39:54.839 --> 39:58.923
and she had all this
confetti popper stuff

39:59.005 --> 40:00.839
and the big check.

40:00.923 --> 40:02.881
We never know whenever
we get a call from Amy

40:02.964 --> 40:05.255
sort of where we're gonna--
it's always good to find out

40:05.339 --> 40:08.005
where she always takes us
to a different area.

40:08.089 --> 40:09.381
- A good surprise.

40:09.464 --> 40:11.756
- Yeah, that's definitely
childproof.

40:11.839 --> 40:13.839
- [laughs]
- I mean, it's big check.

40:13.923 --> 40:16.464
I think it was taller
than her, actually.

40:17.631 --> 40:20.130
- Everything had
to seem very natural.

40:20.214 --> 40:23.130
It had to seem like we had
done this a million times.

40:23.214 --> 40:25.422
We made sure that
I always called Doug, "Doug"

40:25.506 --> 40:27.089
and not "Agent Mathews,"

40:27.172 --> 40:28.673
because it would have
been really bad if suddenly

40:28.756 --> 40:31.172
I was like, "Uh, Agent Mathews,
can you go do this?"

40:31.255 --> 40:34.547
- Amy was really nervous,
the whole time.

40:34.631 --> 40:37.089
[laughs]
So--which was good.

40:37.172 --> 40:38.589
It was healthy to be that way,

40:38.673 --> 40:41.089
'cause I told her I was too,
and I wasn't--you know,

40:41.172 --> 40:42.089
I wasn't lying to her.

40:42.172 --> 40:44.255
She's used to this; I'm not.

40:44.339 --> 40:46.422
Even though I said,
"Oh, I got this," right?

40:46.506 --> 40:50.047
She had no idea that
I had never done this before,

40:50.130 --> 40:51.089
but I loved it.

40:51.172 --> 40:53.130
- There's Mr. Monopoly.
- There he is!

40:53.214 --> 40:55.464
All right.
- It's gotta be sinking in now.

40:55.547 --> 40:57.255
- Now it's official,
Ronald McDonald,

40:57.339 --> 40:59.547
the official signature.

40:59.631 --> 41:04.214
- Doug Mathews could talk to
a wall and get it to respond.

41:04.297 --> 41:06.714
You know, he's got that
little bit of a Southern drawl

41:06.798 --> 41:08.422
and everybody
sort of likes him.

41:08.506 --> 41:10.964
He's the,
"Oh, gosh darn, you won."

41:11.714 --> 41:13.339
- There was no risk
that somebody's gonna think,

41:13.422 --> 41:15.047
"Well, this guy is
an FBI agent,

41:15.130 --> 41:16.798
and this is
an undercover operation."

41:16.881 --> 41:18.964
I mean, nobody--
[laughs]

41:19.047 --> 41:22.130
no FBI agent laughs
as much as this guy does.

41:22.214 --> 41:24.547
- I go, "Wow, this really
looks like there's--

41:24.631 --> 41:26.547
it's had
a woman's touch here."

41:26.631 --> 41:29.964
I mean, it was all
this plaid--just, this shit.

41:30.047 --> 41:32.798
[laughs]
Which is probably why I did it.

41:32.881 --> 41:34.839
[laughing]

41:34.923 --> 41:36.881
And, you know, I said all
kinds of stuff, I was--

41:36.964 --> 41:40.005
again, I was trying to,
you know, move this out,

41:40.089 --> 41:41.631
make everybody seem
real comfortable

41:41.714 --> 41:44.130
with uncomfortable things,
which is what I'm good at.

41:44.214 --> 41:47.381
♪ ♪

41:47.464 --> 41:49.506
- Tell us the story
about how you won

41:49.589 --> 41:51.172
at the Monopoly game,
everything like that,

41:51.255 --> 41:52.214
in your own words.

41:52.297 --> 41:53.339
- Okay.

41:53.422 --> 41:55.172
Um...

41:55.255 --> 41:56.631
day started out
pretty peaceful.

41:56.714 --> 41:57.631
It was a day off,

41:57.714 --> 41:59.881
and I went to the beach
for a while.

41:59.964 --> 42:03.381
I ended up actually
falling asleep at the beach.

42:03.464 --> 42:06.422
And when I woke up,
the wind had come up

42:06.506 --> 42:08.422
and I was covered with sand--

42:08.506 --> 42:10.005
not a lot,
but a little bit of sand--

42:10.089 --> 42:13.005
and I picked up my belongings,
and I headed down

42:13.089 --> 42:15.339
to the water there
to kind of wash my legs off

42:15.422 --> 42:18.506
with the sand,
and I was a little klutzy.

42:18.589 --> 42:20.923
The "People" magazine...
[clears throat]

42:21.005 --> 42:23.798
and my towel
fell out of the backpack,

42:23.881 --> 42:26.631
fell into the water,
and got all wet.

42:26.714 --> 42:29.673
I ended up, uh...
throwing those away

42:29.756 --> 42:31.255
on the way to the car,

42:31.339 --> 42:33.214
and then after...

42:33.297 --> 42:35.255
I was coming home,
I decided to stop and get

42:35.339 --> 42:37.381
provisions for dinner.

42:37.464 --> 42:40.756
So I stopped
at the McQuade's Supermarket

42:40.839 --> 42:42.547
and picked up a few things,

42:42.631 --> 42:44.964
and I had never got a chance
to read the magazine.

42:45.047 --> 42:46.839
And they--there
it was right there

42:46.923 --> 42:48.923
at the checkout stand,
so I bought one.

42:49.005 --> 42:50.923
And when I got home,
I was leafing through it,

42:51.005 --> 42:54.798
and we had
the McDonald's Monopoly game,

42:54.881 --> 42:57.631
and it had instant
prize winners on it--

42:57.714 --> 42:59.923
or they had the quick pick,
whatever you call 'em.

43:00.005 --> 43:01.631
I don't know
what they're called.

43:01.714 --> 43:04.547
Uh, and the first one
I peeled off, I believe,

43:04.631 --> 43:05.839
was Pennsylvania Avenue.

43:05.923 --> 43:07.589
And the second one I peeled off

43:07.673 --> 43:09.339
was a million-dollar
instant prize winner,

43:09.422 --> 43:12.255
and it was like,
"Wow, is this for real?"

43:12.339 --> 43:15.339
And then I, uh...
followed the directions

43:15.422 --> 43:19.172
and made the calls and talked
to the people, and, uh...

43:19.255 --> 43:20.547
it was for real.

43:20.631 --> 43:22.339
- Amy's just used
to getting the story.

43:22.422 --> 43:23.923
But for me,
I'm putting legs to that.

43:24.005 --> 43:28.089
And he was mentioning some
grocery story, and so I go,

43:28.172 --> 43:30.756
"Which one?
Is it right here?"

43:30.839 --> 43:32.214
"Hey, can you take us there?"

43:32.297 --> 43:33.631
He goes, "Sure."

43:33.714 --> 43:35.464
You know, he's feeding
off the energy part.

43:35.547 --> 43:37.422
No, I wasn't
about to stop that.

43:37.506 --> 43:39.964
That was great.
It's a field trip, right?

43:40.047 --> 43:41.923
[engine revving]

43:42.005 --> 43:44.047
I'm getting calls,
"The fuck are you doing?"

43:44.130 --> 43:46.214
"I mean, why are you--what?"
This is, like,

43:46.297 --> 43:49.255
"Are you adlibbing?"
And I'd go, "Hey, Jan."

43:49.339 --> 43:50.631
My camera guy, right?

43:50.714 --> 43:51.589
Can you get this?"

43:51.673 --> 43:53.089
"Yeah, I can get it."

43:53.172 --> 43:54.673
[tires screech]

43:56.172 --> 43:59.422
- Doug struck me as one
of the new breed of agents

43:59.506 --> 44:02.339
who thinks outside
the box, if you will.

44:02.422 --> 44:05.923
But he was gung-ho
from the get-go.

44:07.631 --> 44:10.673
- This is where I got
the, uh, "People" magazine.

44:10.756 --> 44:13.964
And inside we had
the Monopoly game

44:14.047 --> 44:16.255
with the instant
$1 million winner,

44:16.339 --> 44:20.089
and it was great;
it's fantastic!

44:20.172 --> 44:21.506
- Great!
- Got it, okay.

44:21.589 --> 44:24.798
- He's telling us how he won
the prize, all the BS.

44:24.881 --> 44:26.964
His was a magazine-type
thing which, at the time

44:27.047 --> 44:28.839
I didn't even know.
I'm looking over, I go,

44:28.923 --> 44:31.464
"Really? I thought you
got this off the packages."

44:31.547 --> 44:33.547
- And Amy's like,
"Did you read any of that

44:33.631 --> 44:34.714
shit I sent you?"

44:34.798 --> 44:37.589
Right, and I go,
"Of course I did."

44:37.673 --> 44:39.339
Which I may have glossed over.

44:39.422 --> 44:41.756
So I go, "Hey, what'd
you do with the money?"

44:41.839 --> 44:43.506
Why?
Because I want to go

44:43.589 --> 44:45.005
seize that stuff, right?

44:45.089 --> 44:47.255
And he's like,
"I'm buying a boat."

44:47.339 --> 44:48.839
And so I go, "What name

44:48.923 --> 44:50.381
would you have on
the back of your boat?"

44:50.464 --> 44:53.881
And he was like,
"Ruthless Scoundrel."

44:53.964 --> 44:55.047
- One, two, three!

44:55.130 --> 44:56.839
- Thanks, McDonald's.

44:56.923 --> 44:59.589
Hey!
[laughs]

45:00.673 --> 45:03.005
- So I'm reenacting
that, right, and I go,

45:03.089 --> 45:05.297
"So, Michael,
you were on the beach?"

45:05.381 --> 45:07.464
"Yes, and it's right here.
It's this beach."

45:07.547 --> 45:10.005
And I go, "Really?
Take us to it."

45:10.089 --> 45:13.005
And I didn't care what that
meant to my camera guy, right?

45:13.089 --> 45:15.589
He's like, "Are you--fuck,
are you kidding me?

45:15.673 --> 45:17.964
I gotta--the damn beach?"

45:18.047 --> 45:19.881
- There's always somebody

45:19.964 --> 45:22.714
that could respond
tactically, if needed.

45:22.798 --> 45:25.964
But if something went south,

45:26.047 --> 45:28.297
between the time
something went south

45:28.381 --> 45:30.005
and the time they got there...

45:30.089 --> 45:33.047
[dramatic music]

45:33.130 --> 45:35.130
♪ ♪

45:35.214 --> 45:37.798
Don't do anything stupid.

45:37.881 --> 45:39.339
♪ ♪

45:39.422 --> 45:41.506
- Doug, you know,
he was a professional,

45:41.589 --> 45:43.297
but he also did
like to have fun.

45:43.381 --> 45:45.547
So he loved to tease me

45:45.631 --> 45:47.339
and kept me on my toes.

45:47.422 --> 45:49.214
- This is what
makes my fun meter go.

45:49.297 --> 45:51.297
Amy's back there going,
"Look at these shoes I have,"

45:51.381 --> 45:53.005
and I'm not looking
at shit like that.

45:53.089 --> 45:54.714
I mean, "Take your high heels--
why are you wearing

45:54.798 --> 45:55.673
high heels anyway?"

45:55.756 --> 45:56.756
And she's like, "Are you--"

45:56.839 --> 45:59.172
you know, she was
getting on to me about,

45:59.255 --> 46:01.047
"Hey, can you plan
this better?"

46:01.130 --> 46:02.130
But I didn't know.

46:02.214 --> 46:03.506
- Can you get enough sound

46:03.589 --> 46:05.005
if he tells
the story one more time?

46:05.089 --> 46:06.464
- You need it?

46:06.547 --> 46:08.172
We could try it.
- Okay.

46:08.255 --> 46:10.839
- [chuckles]
- Anybody noticing you yet?

46:10.923 --> 46:12.255
- Not really.

46:12.339 --> 46:14.005
- Good.

46:16.798 --> 46:18.172
- When Doug's at the house,

46:18.255 --> 46:20.047
it was a controlled
environment.

46:20.130 --> 46:21.673
When you're out
in the real world,

46:21.756 --> 46:23.255
there's nothing controlled.

46:23.339 --> 46:25.047
You're always a little worried

46:25.130 --> 46:28.881
the operation and the case
could be compromised.

46:28.964 --> 46:31.964
- Uh, this is where I lost
my "People" magazine.

46:32.047 --> 46:34.130
I'm glad that after
the beach I stopped

46:34.214 --> 46:36.255
and picked up another one
because when I did,

46:36.339 --> 46:39.005
I found the McDonald's
Monopoly Game,

46:39.089 --> 46:41.673
$1 million
instant prize winner.

46:41.756 --> 46:43.547
- Great.
Okay, good.

46:43.631 --> 46:46.130
- Obviously, you know,
this was Doug's very first

46:46.214 --> 46:49.631
undercover, and so you'd
wanna try to keep him

46:49.714 --> 46:53.297
under control,
keep him sedated,

46:53.381 --> 46:54.464
so to speak.

46:54.547 --> 46:56.172
They don't make it easy.

46:56.255 --> 46:58.297
- So I'm like,
"Man, I got plenty.

46:58.381 --> 46:59.464
I got enough."

46:59.547 --> 47:01.339
- Can I do a couple
of artsy things,

47:01.422 --> 47:03.881
okay, real quick?

47:03.964 --> 47:06.172
- Hey.
[laughs]

47:06.255 --> 47:08.130
- You know, he'd stand
there smiling, and you know,

47:08.214 --> 47:09.631
you're doing
all this artsy stuff,

47:09.714 --> 47:13.923
and then some kid ran up
and grabbed the check.

47:14.005 --> 47:16.005
To run away with it.

47:16.756 --> 47:19.339
- Like, I'm gonna let
this evidence just walk?

47:19.422 --> 47:20.297
No way.

47:20.381 --> 47:22.255
And I'm trucking
down the beach...

47:22.339 --> 47:25.673
- And it's like,
"Dude, it's not real."

47:25.756 --> 47:26.673
- It was bad news.

47:26.756 --> 47:29.130
That's not a good problem
to have,

47:29.214 --> 47:30.339
being an undercover agent.

47:30.422 --> 47:32.339
- And this guy is hammered.

47:32.422 --> 47:33.631
Fortunately, he's running,
like,

47:33.714 --> 47:36.881
in a zigzag,
so it's easy to catch.

47:36.964 --> 47:39.673
This kid, he was, like,
full of sand in his mouth

47:39.756 --> 47:42.130
and crap and I'm like,
"Dude..."

47:42.214 --> 47:43.673
[stammers]

47:43.756 --> 47:45.673
"I don't know what I'm gonna
do with all this sand."

47:45.756 --> 47:49.339
And he's like,
"Man, I just saw, like,

47:49.422 --> 47:52.839
"all those zeros and thought...

47:52.923 --> 47:54.172
I'm just gonna go take it."

47:54.255 --> 47:55.964
And I can't even remember
where he wandered off,

47:56.047 --> 47:58.756
but he was out of there;
we never saw him again.

47:58.839 --> 48:00.339
[bombastic music]

48:00.422 --> 48:02.297
- Sometimes on a case,

48:02.381 --> 48:04.923
being lucky is better
than being good.

48:05.005 --> 48:08.714
- No Asics, no nothing,
and we still caught that dude,

48:08.798 --> 48:11.047
of course, he was hammered,
and we were not.

48:11.130 --> 48:13.339
And we did get the check back.

48:13.422 --> 48:18.547
♪ ♪

48:18.631 --> 48:20.756
[engine turns over]

48:21.673 --> 48:24.673
It worked great.
Amy was phenomenal.

48:24.756 --> 48:29.130
And I'm like, "Man,
undercover is awesome."

48:29.214 --> 48:31.422
[laughing]

48:33.589 --> 48:36.464
Turned out it really
tickled our wire up.

48:36.547 --> 48:39.339
Michael Hoover
would be on the phones

48:39.422 --> 48:40.631
which is great,
because then we were listening

48:40.714 --> 48:41.923
to that and recording it.

48:42.005 --> 48:43.714
You know, again,
it got him comfortable.

48:43.798 --> 48:45.839
It actually worked.
You know, all that works.

48:45.964 --> 48:48.673
[dramatic music]

48:48.756 --> 48:50.130
♪ ♪

48:50.214 --> 48:52.422
- At that time,
I was here in Jacksonville

48:52.506 --> 48:54.756
in the--
what we call wire room.

48:54.839 --> 48:57.631
We were listening in
for what we hoped to be

48:57.714 --> 49:01.589
a telephone call
to this Uncle Jerry.

49:01.673 --> 49:04.631
And immediately
there's a phone call

49:04.714 --> 49:07.839
by Mr. Hoover to Mr. Glomb
down in South Florida.

49:07.923 --> 49:09.756
♪ ♪

49:09.839 --> 49:11.923
- We were up on
three or four phones.

49:12.005 --> 49:14.839
One was this guy,
Andrew Glomb.

49:14.923 --> 49:18.923
I mean, Andrew Glomb was
the guy with a checkered past.

49:19.005 --> 49:21.297
He had previously convicted
for some drug charges

49:21.381 --> 49:23.589
on the federal side
with the DEA.

49:23.673 --> 49:24.673
♪ ♪

49:24.756 --> 49:26.506
- He had been in a drug
trafficking thing.

49:26.589 --> 49:29.381
He was a fugitive for a while,
eventually got arrested,

49:29.464 --> 49:32.297
and he did some time.

49:32.381 --> 49:35.798
And so, Mr. Hoover
had called Mr. Glomb.

49:35.881 --> 49:38.214
- Ring, ring.
Ring, ring.

49:38.297 --> 49:40.923
"Hello?"
"Yeah, Andy."

49:41.005 --> 49:42.381
That's Andy Glomb.

49:42.464 --> 49:45.339
"Andy, they were here.
They believed everything.

49:45.422 --> 49:47.964
"Everything I told them
about the winning the ticket

49:48.047 --> 49:50.130
on that 'People' magazine."

49:50.214 --> 49:52.964
- "And I was telling them,
'I did this, and I did that.'"

49:53.047 --> 49:56.172
And at the very same time,
I'm on my cell phone

49:56.255 --> 49:58.297
talking to Doug Mathews

49:58.381 --> 50:00.422
and telling him,
"Listen to this."

50:00.506 --> 50:01.798
♪ ♪

50:01.881 --> 50:04.464
- The feeling from him
on the phone call was,

50:04.547 --> 50:06.631
"Man, I got them snowed,
they bel--"

50:06.714 --> 50:07.964
you know, it was that--
it was that--

50:08.047 --> 50:09.673
I mean, it was perfect.

50:09.756 --> 50:11.798
It's exactly what you're after.

50:11.881 --> 50:13.673
He's talking, "Man,
you're not gonna believe it.

50:13.756 --> 50:16.673
"This director asked
about the name of my boat

50:16.756 --> 50:18.839
and I said,
'Ruthless Scoundrel.'"

50:18.923 --> 50:20.506
And they're just laughing
on the phone,

50:20.589 --> 50:23.964
how much--how funny that was
to them because they knew

50:24.047 --> 50:27.714
they had lied and had stolen
this money from McDonald's.

50:27.798 --> 50:31.547
- In that call, effectively
what he's doing is confirming

50:31.631 --> 50:35.673
beyond any doubt that,
you know, he didn't win it.

50:35.756 --> 50:38.506
♪ ♪

50:38.589 --> 50:40.839
- It just doesn't get
any better than that.

50:40.923 --> 50:42.506
It's like high fives.

50:42.589 --> 50:45.464
- That was why you get up
on these wiretaps.

50:45.547 --> 50:47.422
So we're hearing
how they did it.

50:47.506 --> 50:50.673
♪ ♪

50:50.756 --> 50:54.381
At the time, we didn't
know how big this was.

50:54.464 --> 50:56.798
We knew of some,
but we didn't know it all.

50:56.881 --> 51:00.923
It was amazing to me
how little we did know.

51:01.005 --> 51:03.673
[phones ringing]

51:03.756 --> 51:10.798
♪ ♪

51:15.297 --> 51:19.089
The spider web of all--
like, we had this Uncle Jerry.

51:19.172 --> 51:21.673
Everything was
very general, nebulous.

51:21.756 --> 51:24.047
We still didn't know,
you got to remember, like,

51:24.130 --> 51:27.172
we still didn't know
who this Jerry person was,

51:27.255 --> 51:28.881
if there even was a Jerry.

51:28.964 --> 51:32.047
So all of the newer agents,
we were on the wiretaps

51:32.130 --> 51:35.714
to find out more about
the depths of this scheme.

51:35.798 --> 51:37.673
- Back then I was a new agent,

51:37.756 --> 51:40.547
and my first assignment
when I was brought in

51:40.631 --> 51:42.798
was to work the wire.

51:43.964 --> 51:47.214
The Title III has to be
monitored full-time, 24/7.

51:47.297 --> 51:48.923
You hear the phone call,
you grab your headset,

51:49.005 --> 51:51.506
you put it on,
you listen to the call.

51:51.589 --> 51:53.297
- We're listening
in the wire room

51:53.381 --> 51:55.881
and I'm hearing, you know,
the name Uncle Jerry

51:55.964 --> 51:58.214
thrown around on the phone.

51:58.297 --> 51:59.881
"Uncle Jerry, Uncle Jerry.

51:59.964 --> 52:03.756
You don't wanna make
Uncle Jerry upset."

52:03.839 --> 52:06.756
- Well, I do remember
clearly feeling like

52:06.839 --> 52:09.547
I was in New York and I was
listening to a mobster

52:09.631 --> 52:11.923
talking about running
his mafia empire,

52:12.005 --> 52:15.506
some mafia don, 'cause that's
kind of how this guy came off.

52:15.589 --> 52:17.631
♪ ♪

52:17.714 --> 52:19.964
- So we had
to find Uncle Jerry.

52:20.047 --> 52:22.172
I mean, how do you do that?

52:22.255 --> 52:28.089
♪ ♪

52:28.172 --> 52:30.297
- We did an analysis

52:30.381 --> 52:33.881
of phone records
from past winners.

52:33.964 --> 52:36.798
You look for
that common number.

52:36.881 --> 52:38.923
- We knew when they won
the prizes, what year,

52:39.005 --> 52:42.798
and we could probably cord it
off to a month, so I think--

52:42.881 --> 52:45.631
I think we backed up two
and went forward two.

52:45.714 --> 52:48.130
♪ ♪

52:48.214 --> 52:52.130
And we went and pulled
the phone numbers coming in

52:52.214 --> 52:55.381
and going out
for this period of time.

52:55.464 --> 52:58.923
♪ ♪

52:59.005 --> 53:01.506
- Lo and behold,
each of their phone numbers

53:01.589 --> 53:03.673
were calling common numbers.

53:03.756 --> 53:08.923
- We saw the activity
heavy coming in right before

53:09.005 --> 53:11.005
the prize was awarded
or claimed,

53:11.089 --> 53:13.589
and then heavy right after it,
and then nothing.

53:13.673 --> 53:15.214
And then none
of them were related;

53:15.297 --> 53:17.172
they didn't know each other.

53:17.255 --> 53:19.839
All were hitting that number.

53:19.923 --> 53:26.673
♪ ♪

53:26.756 --> 53:30.673
- All these phone calls
include one person...

53:30.756 --> 53:32.255
♪ ♪

53:32.339 --> 53:34.631
Jerome Jacobson.

53:34.714 --> 53:36.714
Also known as...

53:36.798 --> 53:38.214
Jerry Jacobson.

53:38.297 --> 53:42.631
The absolute head of security
for Simon Marketing.

53:42.714 --> 53:45.964
♪ ♪

53:46.047 --> 53:49.005
[funky music]

53:49.089 --> 53:56.130
♪ ♪

54:36.089 --> 54:38.297
[bright tone]

54:40.506 --> 54:42.923
There was a wide net
of individuals who were willing

54:43.005 --> 54:45.089
to participate
in this fraud scheme.

54:45.172 --> 54:46.172
♪ (UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

54:46.255 --> 54:49.130
WOMAN:
It got really big, really fast.

54:49.673 --> 54:51.798
There was one
nagging question mark...

54:53.506 --> 54:54.756
Who is Uncle Jerry?

54:55.172 --> 54:56.005
(CASH REGISTER DINGS)

54:56.214 --> 54:58.297
We were racking up
incredible evidence

54:58.381 --> 54:59.756
and discovering new people.

55:00.798 --> 55:03.881
We found out that there was
another Jerry involved in this.

55:04.172 --> 55:06.172
MAN: He took this little,
small operation,

55:06.255 --> 55:07.756
and made it huge.

55:08.881 --> 55:11.881
As soon as I got that check,
things changed.

55:12.923 --> 55:15.130
"You gonna ride with us,
and you gonna do what we say.

55:15.339 --> 55:16.464
And you gonna do it right."

55:16.547 --> 55:19.881
I'm not a dumb person,
but I did a dumb thing.

55:20.214 --> 55:22.964
No one can stand in front
of a mirror and say

55:23.047 --> 55:24.673
they've never done something...

55:25.214 --> 55:27.089
that they wish
they could take back.

55:27.714 --> 55:30.214
I'mma lay all my cards on
the table and tell everything.

55:30.881 --> 55:34.422
MAN 2: We were just building
the puzzle from all the pieces.

55:34.506 --> 55:35.339
(POLICE SIREN BLARES)

55:35.673 --> 55:37.130
MAN 3: We started finding
other middle-men.

55:37.214 --> 55:40.589
The money got too big to not
take a bigger piece of that pie.

55:41.130 --> 55:44.089
It could've been a possible hit
to get him out of the situation.

55:44.756 --> 55:46.964
WOMAN 2: A little teardrop
came down my face.

55:47.047 --> 55:49.589
I thought, "I'm never
gonna get out of this."

55:50.172 --> 55:51.172
(CASH REGISTER DINGS)

55:51.255 --> 55:52.756
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
